    <h2 id="science-of-aging">Why Your Skin Loses Collagen — and What Science Says About Supplementation</h2>

    <p>Skin aging is driven by two interconnected processes: intrinsic aging (genetically programmed collagen decline) and extrinsic aging (environmental damage from UV radiation, pollution, and oxidative stress). Starting around age 25, the body's collagen production decreases by approximately 1 to 1.5% per year. By age 50, most adults have lost 25 to 30% of their skin's collagen content, resulting in reduced elasticity, increased wrinkle depth, and diminished moisture retention. Anti-aging gummies target both processes — collagen peptides address the production deficit while antioxidants neutralize the environmental damage that accelerates breakdown.</p>

